<AbstractNarration> This project deals with two major areas of mathematical relativity&lt;br/&gt;which border on the fields of 3-manifold topology on the one hand and&lt;br/&gt;numerical/experimental relativity on the other. The first research&lt;br/&gt;topic treats the question of how the spatial topology of the universe&lt;br/&gt;affects its long-time evolution. The second topic involves the&lt;br/&gt;development of an efficient and accurate numerical scheme for the&lt;br/&gt;computation of gravitational waves produced by colliding black holes.&lt;br/&gt; The importance of the first topic is that it seeks to unify the study&lt;br/&gt;of the evolutionary properties of the universe with various&lt;br/&gt;geometrization results and conjectures from pure mathematics, thereby&lt;br/&gt;broadening the scope of results in either field of study. The&lt;br/&gt;importance of the second topic is that it seeks to support the&lt;br/&gt;experimental search for gravitational waves by improving the&lt;br/&gt;theoretical understanding of possible sources of such waves.</AbstractNarration>
